<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-523-863  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 523 863.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Oct 15 1990 v219 n17 p19(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Back to business. (customer premises telephone equipment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Karpinski, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There is both bad news and good news for distributors of customerpremises equipment (CPE) today: the bad news is that the PBX andkey system markets are flat; the good news is that ancillarymarkets - voice add-ons, data equipment, Centrex and long-distancereselling - offer new revenue sources for interconnect companies.andO;According to data provided by the North AmericanTelecommunications Association, the PBX market has held steady at$3 billion during the past few years.andP;  The data equipment market,by comparison, grew from $5.1 billion to $7 billion, and the voiceprocessing market, including automatic call distributors,automated attendants and voice mail equipment, increased from $800million to $1.5 billion.andP;  To be successful, an interconnect mustbe both aggressive and service-oriented.andP;  Suppliers, says anindustry exec, must be 'integrated with their customers' needs.'andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Communications EquipmentTelephone systemsPBXNorth American Telecommunications AssociationMarket Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   PBX shipments by distribution channel. (graph)Key/hybrid shipments by distribution channel. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>